# The what, the why, & the how

## What is differential expression?

- Looking for a difference in gene transcript abundance between experimental groups. 
- So that means you can find specific genes that have changed there expression.
- Which genes are changing? How many? What do those genes do?
- But this leads to the obvious question, what defines a change?
  - Changes greater than what would be expected by random variation. 
  - Want only significant changes. That means statistics!
  - We will get into that a bit later.


## Why use differential expression?

- Melissa did a great job providing motivation for doing transcriptomics, so I won't go into much detail here to save time. 
- But if we are fundamentally interested in how Genotype leads to Phenotype then investigating transcription is one step closer to the phenotype.
- Could potentially give insight into how different populations have diverged or how they react to different environmental conditions or acclimations.

# Normalization

So what we have at the end here is something that looks a bit like a data matrix or gene count table, where each row is a specfic gene and each column is a sample

## Why normalize?

There are two main problems that normalization is trying to address

- Differences in library sizes
- Differences in library composition

The differences in library sizes basically is just a question of sequencing depth. If there are twice as many raw counts counts for  

```{r, eval=FALSE}
df <- tibble(gene = c("Act5C", "Hsp70a", "lola", "Rab4"),
             samp_1 = c(120, 50, 75, 0),
             samp_2 = c(60, 25, 37, 0),
             samp_3 = c(22, 9, 14, 200))


df_log <- df %>%
  mutate(samp_1 = log(samp_1),
         samp_2 = log(samp_2),
         samp_3 = log(samp_3))



df_log %>%
  pivot_longer(contains("samp_"), names_to = "sample", values_to = "count") %>%
  group_by(gene) %>%
  summarize(avg = mean(count)) %>%
  full_join(df) %>%
  select(gene, contains("samp"), avg)

df_sum <- df_log %>%
  pivot_longer(contains("samp_"), names_to = "sample", values_to = "count") %>%
  group_by(sample) %>%
  summarize(sum = sum(count)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = "sample", values_from = "sum") %>%
  mutate(gene = c("sum")) %>%
  bind_rows(df) %>%
  arrange(gene) %>%
  select(gene, everything()) 

df %>%
  pivot_longer(contains("samp_"), names_to = "sample", values_to = "count") %>%
  group_by(gene) %>%
  summarize(avg = mean(count)) %>%
  full_join(df_sum) %>%
  select(gene, contains("samp"), avg)
```

## Types of Normalization

Okay so, then how do they address those problems in the normalization process?

There are many procedures out there:

- Counts per million (CPM) - just accounts for sequencing depth
- Transcripts per kilobase million (TPKM) - accounts for sequencing depth and gene length
- Fragments per kilobase million (FPKM) - accounts for sequencing depth and gene length 
- edgeR - sequencing depth, composition, and gene length
- DESeq2 - sequencing depth and RNA composition (for differential expression between samples only - not for within sample comparisons)

* The number of reads can be affected by the gene length and GC content. But if you are only interested in differential expression among different samples or groups. Then you do not have to normalize for this. Only if you were doing within sample comparisons.

I will just spend some time going into some detail on DESeq2's normalization method because:

- DESeq2 is one of the more popular packages out there
- it also happens to be what we will use with our data on Wednesday

## DESeq2 normalization

[Helpful video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFB993xufUU)

  1. Log transformation (DESeq2 uses the natural log as it is the default in R)
  2. Gene average across samples
  3. Genes with `-Inf` are filtered out (_i.e._ raw count = 0)
  4. Subtract log-transfomed counts from gene average (creates a ratio because it is subtraction of logs)
  5. Get per sample median of those log-ratios across all genes
  6. Raise base e to that median value -> that is your scaling factor
  7. Divide the original

# Enrichment analysis

Okay so we found a bunch of genes changing, but how do we make sense out of all of the information. You can either search through it by hand, looking for your favorite genes or the genes with greatest relative fold change, or lowest p-value or something. But people have developed ways of trying to look for entire sets of genes or functional pathways that are changing. There are multiple functional databases that you can query and multiple ways that you can test for enrichment of particular gene sets.

## Functional databases (Gene sets)

GO and KEGG are among the more popular functional databases for analyzing gene sets. Pfam one of the databases that were used in the paper we read for today.

### Gene Ontology (GO)

[Gene Ontology overview](http://geneontology.org/docs/ontology-documentation/)

- **Molecular function** - molecular activities performed by gene products
  - catalytic activity 
    - adenylate cyclase activity
  - transporter activity
    - Toll-like receptor binding.
- **Biological process** - the larger biological processes that the gene product is involved in
  - DNA repair
    - pyrimidine nucleobase biosynthetic process
  - signal transduction
    - glucose transmembrane transport
- **Cellular component** - cellular compartments or macromolecular complexes where the gene product performs its function
  - mitochondria
  - ribosome
  
There is a hierarchy of terms.
![](http://geneontology.org/assets/hexose-biosynthetic-process.png)

### KEGG pathway

[Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes](https://www.genome.jp/kegg/pathway.html) is similarly structured with sub sets. Genetic information processing -> Transcription -> Spliceosome 

![](https://www.genome.jp/kegg/pathway/ko/ko03040.png)

### Pfam: Protien families

Semi-automated method of curating protein family information to help annotate genomes.

[Example of a _Pfam_ entry](https://pfam.xfam.org/family/PF02171)
